<body data-topic="ifelse">
    <div class="container">
        <h1 class="mb-4">🔀 If - Else</h1>

        <p><strong>If - Else</strong> statements allow your program to <strong>make decisions</strong>. They tell your computer: “If this is true, do this. Otherwise, do something else.”</p>

        <p>You already use this logic in real life:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>If it rains → take an umbrella</li>
            <li>If you are hungry → eat</li>
            <li>If it's your birthday → celebrate!</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>📘 What is an If Statement?</h2>
        <p>An <strong>if</strong> checks a condition. If the condition is true, the code inside the block runs.</p>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="code-header">Basic Example</div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre>
if (condition) {
    // code that runs if the condition is true
}
</pre>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>📘 What is an Else Statement?</h2>
        <p><strong>else</strong> runs only when the condition in <strong>if</strong> is NOT true.</p>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="code-header">If + Else Example</div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre>
if (condition) {
    // true branch
} else {
    // false branch
}
</pre>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>🎯 Real Example: Teenager Check</h2>
        <p>If the person is 13 or older → they are a teenager.</p>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="form-check form-switch mb-2">
                <input class="form-check-input" type="checkbox" id="teenagerToggle" onchange="convertCode('teenager')">
                <label class="form-check-label" for="teenagerToggle">Convert to C#</label>
            </div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre class="codeBlock" id="teenagerCode">
int age = 14;
if (age >= 13) {
    cout << "You are a teenager!";
} else {
    cout << "You are not a teenager.";
}
</pre>
            </div>
            <div class="result-box" id="teenagerResult">
                ➡ <strong>Result:</strong> You are a teenager!<br>
                <em>Explanation:</em> The variable <code>age</code> is 14, which is greater than or equal to 13, so the code inside the <strong>if</strong> block runs.
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>🟦 Only If (No Else)</h2>
        <p>Sometimes you only want to run code when something is true.</p>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="form-check form-switch mb-2">
                <input class="form-check-input" type="checkbox" id="ifOnlyToggle" onchange="convertCode('ifonly')">
                <label class="form-check-label" for="ifOnlyToggle">Convert to C#</label>
            </div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre class="codeBlock" id="ifOnlyCode">
int age = 20;
if (age > 18) {
    cout << "You can vote!";
}
</pre>
            </div>
            <div class="result-box" id="ifOnlyResult">
                ➡ <strong>Result:</strong> You can vote!<br>
                <em>Explanation:</em> The variable <code>age</code> is 20, which is greater than 18, so the <strong>if</strong> block executes.
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>🟨 Multiple Conditions (Else If)</h2>
        <p>Use <strong>else if</strong> when you need more than two choices.</p>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="form-check form-switch mb-2">
                <input class="form-check-input" type="checkbox" id="elseifToggle" onchange="convertCode('elseif')">
                <label class="form-check-label" for="elseifToggle">Convert to C#</label>
            </div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre class="codeBlock" id="elseifCode">
int grade = 85;

if (grade >= 90) {
    cout << "Excellent!";
}
else if (grade >= 75) {
    cout << "Good job!";
}
else if (grade >= 60) {
    cout << "You passed!";
}
else {
    cout << "Try again!";
}
</pre>
            </div>
            <div class="result-box" id="elseifResult">
                ➡ <strong>Result:</strong> Good job!<br>
                <em>Explanation:</em> <code>grade</code> is 85, which is >= 75 but < 90, so the second <strong>else if</strong> block runs.
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>📚 Example: Checking Temperature</h2>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="form-check form-switch mb-2">
                <input class="form-check-input" type="checkbox" id="tempToggle" onchange="convertCode('temp')">
                <label class="form-check-label" for="tempToggle">Convert to C#</label>
            </div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre class="codeBlock" id="tempCode">
int temp = 30;

if (temp > 35) {
    cout << "It's very hot!";
}
else if (temp > 20) {
    cout << "Nice weather!";
}
else if (temp > 5) {
    cout << "It's cold!";
}
else {
    cout << "It's freezing!";
}
</pre>
            </div>
            <div class="result-box" id="tempResult">
                ➡ <strong>Result:</strong> Nice weather!<br>
                <em>Explanation:</em> <code>temp</code> is 30, which is > 20 but ≤ 35, so the second <strong>else if</strong> block runs.
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>🧠 Visual Diagram</h2>

        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="code-header">Decision Flow</div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre>
         [Condition True?]
                |
          Yes /   \ No
          |         |
   Run IF code   Run ELSE code
</pre>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>🎉 Summary</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>If</strong> runs only when a condition is true</li>
            <li><strong>Else</strong> runs when false</li>
            <li><strong>Else if</strong> checks more possibilities</li>
            <li>Used for decisions like age, temperature, grades…</li>
        </ul>

